It is a well-established result in mechanism design that submitting one's true preference list is a dominant strategy for the proposing agents (Parents) in the DA algorithm, guaranteeing the best possible stable assignment for that parent relative to all submitted lists. Part 2 of the procedure introduces waivers for 'blocking parents' and reruns Part 1. Since the definition of a blocking parent depends on discrepancies between temporary and final admissions in Part 1, and the resulting waivers only modify *other* parents' lists (and the subsequent rerun results in a final stable matching based on the modified lists), Parent_B cannot improve their outcome by misrepresenting their preferences. The true preference list guarantees the Parent-Optimal stable matching outcome from the initial DA run, and this outcome is the best Parent_B can hope for. Submitting the true list maximizes Parent_B's chance of securing a high-ranked school.

The matching environment described in Part 1 is the Parent-Proposing Deferred Acceptance (DA) algorithm. In this type of centralized mechanism, when one side (Parents) proposes, the resulting stable matching is the 'proposer-pessimal' stable matching. A fundamental result in matching theory (Strategy-Proofness of DA) states that the proposing agents cannot unilaterally submit a false preference list to obtain a better match than they would by submitting their true preferences, provided that all other agents report truthfully.
